			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/mergers-acquisitions/">Mergers &amp; Acquisitions</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Markets Buoyant, Merger Activity Picks Up</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Gelles			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-01-01T21:32:52+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 1, 2014 4:32 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 1, 2014 4:32 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/02/business/dbpix-merger/dbpix-merger-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/02/business/dbpix-merger/dbpix-merger-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/02/business/dbpix-merger/dbpix-merger-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002627945" width="190" height="127" alt="Tetsuro Higashi, left, the chairman of Tokyo Electron, with Gary Dickerson, the chief of Applied Materials in September, when the two announced an all-stock, cross-border merger deal."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Tetsuro Higashi, left, the chairman of Tokyo Electron, with Gary Dickerson, the chief of Applied Materials in September, when the two announced an all-stock, cross-border merger deal.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Yoshikazu Tsuno/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
What may have been the most auspicious deal of late was not the biggest or the most groundbreaking of mergers. It was just one that took a little gumption.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In September, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=AMAT&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Applied Materials Inc">Applied Materials</a>, a California maker of semiconductor manufacturing equipment, agreed to acquire its rival, Tokyo Electron, in a deal valued at more than $9 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As an all-stock, cross-border deal, it was the kind of tricky merger that telegraphed executivesâ confidence and an appetite to make even slightly risky deals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt was when the light bulb went on,â a senior deal maker said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Are the animal spirits finally returning to the corporate world?</p>
<div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/01/02/business/dealbook/merger.html"> <img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/graphic_icon.gif" alt="Graphic" width="11" height="11"  border="0">: Plotting Strategic Deals</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the United States, they appear to be. While global deal-making was basically flat for a fourth consecutive year, annual volume in the United States was up 11 percent in 2013 compared with the previous year, according to <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TRI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Thomson Reuters Corporation">Thomson Reuters</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Companies from New York to San Francisco announced <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/01/02/business/dealbook/merger.html" title="Graphic depicting M.&#038;A. activity.">more than $1 trillion worth of deals during the year</a>, the most since the financial crisis. That led the United States to account for 43 percent of all deals worldwide, the biggest proportion since 2001.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatâs more, activity picked up over the final two quarters, with volumes rising sharply from the first six months of the year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThereâs a feeling of a more stable backdrop that executives think will be with us for the foreseeable quarters,â said Blair W. Effron, co-founder of Centerview Partners, an independent investment bank. âI didnât have a sense of that at the end of 2012 or 2011.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And with markets buoyant thanks to relative stability in Washington and around the globe, as well as moderate growth from corporations, the bankers and lawyers that advise companies on mergers and acquisitions are more optimistic than they have been in years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âFrom a macroeconomic perspective, we have a stronger economy, we have Congress behaving more responsibly, and we have all appearances of stability at the Fed,â said Scott A. Barshay, head of the corporate department at Cravath, Swaine &#038; Moore, one of the top law firms on Wall Street. âC.E.O.âs can look forward and say, âI donât see any near-term economic bumps.â â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This stability is leading executives and directors to return to the business of plotting transformative deals that might take months or even years to execute, and even longer to pay dividends.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBoards are thinking about their goals not just tactically in a one-year 2014 increment, but more strategically for the longer term,â Mr. Effron said. âCompanies are looking further down the field.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Centerview worked on three of the biggest deals of the year, advising <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=HNZ&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about HJ Heinz Company">H. J. Heinz</a> on its $23 billion sale to 3G Capital and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BRK.A&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Berkshire Hathaway Inc">Berkshire Hathaway</a>, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GE&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about General Electric Company">General Electric</a> on its sale of the remainder of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/nbc_universal/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about NBC Universal.">NBCUniversal</a> to <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=CMCSA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Comcast Corporation">Comcast</a> for $16.7 billion, and Silver Lake Partners on its role in the buyout of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DELL&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Dell Inc">Dell</a> for $24.9 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other boutique investment banks like Centerview continued to secure advisory roles on the biggest deals of the year. LionTree Advisors, a small firm focusing on media deals, advised <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=LBTYA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Liberty Global Inc">Liberty Global</a> on its $16 billion deal for <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=VMED&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Virgin Media Inc">Virgin Media</a>, while Moelis &#038; Company advised Omnicom on its $35.1 billion merger with Publicis, which was advised by Rothschild.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even the largest deal of the year â <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=VZ&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Verizon Communications Inc">Verizon</a> Communicationâs $130 billion purchase from <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=VOD&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Vodafone Group Plc">Vodafone</a> of the stake in Verizon Wireless it did not already own â had upstarts among the big banks like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a>. Both Guggenheim Securities and Paul J. Taubman, the former <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Morgan Stanley">Morgan Stanley</a> banker who helped strike the original deal, advised Verizon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet the big banks continued to advise on most deals, and collect the most fees. Goldman, followed by JPMorgan, led advisers in deals by volume both in the United States and worldwide last year. The two banks also collected the most fees for their work, earning an estimated $1.5 billion and $1.3 billion for their advisory roles, according to Dealogic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Verizon deal with Vodafone, one of the largest transactions ever, had been expected for years. But with interest rates low because of the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a>âs sustained stimulus program, Verizon was finally compelled to act before rates began creeping up. (That advantage was underscored when Verizon sold a record $49 billion of investment-grade corporate debt at once to help pay for the acquisition.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis era of low interest rates has encouraged companies to consolidate and clean up some structural inefficiencies,â said Michael Carr, head of Goldman Sachsâs mergers and acquisitions group in Americas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, while many factors encouraged merger activity, one phenomenon that once drove deals â activist investors â became something of a depressant. Activists were once feared for their ability to shake up company, spurring it to make deals with competitors or test the market for a sale.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To some degree that was still the case. Activists occasionally prodded smaller companies to sell themselves, and in other cases encouraged big conglomerates to dispose of noncore units. <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/p/nelson_peltz/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Nelson Peltz.">Nelson Peltz</a>, for example, pushed for a big spinoff at DuPont.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âActivism has been a positive influence on some companies, making them more introspective,â said Chris Ventresca, co-head of global mergers and acquisitions at JPMorgan. âCompanies are realizing that if they donât look at what is core and noncore, someone will do it for them.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But by and large, activists focused more on capital allocation than on deals. Moreover, many advisers said that executives now feared that spending money on a deal rather than returning it to shareholders would invite activist scrutiny.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCompanies that have activists in their stock generally do not do acquisitions,â Mr. Barshay of Cravath said. âThe activists are completely focused on returning capital to shareholders.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Regardless, United States companies forged ahead with deals, and were often rewarded when they did. Another factor that emboldened companies to make more deals is that for the most part, the markets rewarded deals that immediately added to earnings. According to Goldman Sachs, in about two-thirds of the deals in 2013, the buyerâs stock price increased on average more than 5 percent on a sustained basis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs giving people confidence that despite the scrutiny of activist investors, companies can really add value through M.&#038;A.,â Mr. Carr of Goldman said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Looking ahead to 2014, deal makers say companies could be prompted to make deals for a number of reasons.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One is that with stock markets riding high, companies will probably feel pressure to demonstrate sustained growth to validate their share prices.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe pressure is building for companies to justify their trading multiples,â Mr. Ventresca of JPMorgan said. âIt will be hard to deliver that organically, so you have to look for inorganic growth.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Certain sectors could also set off rounds of megadeals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year, many companies in the telecommunications industry made deals. Besides the Verizon and Vodafone megadeal, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=SFTBF&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about SOFTBANK Corporation">SoftBank</a> took control of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=S&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Sprint Nextel Corporation">Sprint</a> in a $21.6 billion deal, and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TMUS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about T-Mobile Us Inc.">T-Mobile</a> and MetroPCS announced a multibillion-dollar reverse merger.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While some telecommunications activity could continue, with Sprint reportedly looking at a bid for T-Mobile, 2014 could have a spate of cable television deals. Charter Communications, backed by <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/john_c_malone/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about John C. Malone.">John C. Malone</a>âs <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=LMCA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Liberty Media Corp">Liberty Media</a>, is preparing to make an offer for <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TWC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Time Warner Cable Inc">Time Warner Cable</a>. But Comcast, the nationâs largest cable operator, is considering a spoiler bid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If either deal happens, it could kick off a wave of consolidation of both cable operators and cable networks, which could look to gain negotiating power by increasing their scale.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll year weâve had strong equity markets, cheap debt and ho-hum M.&#038;A.,â Mr. Barshay said. âThat usually doesnât happen and it is finally starting to change. Weâre seeing it in a spate of recent deals and weâre seeing it in the pipeline.â</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
